ble-content"><div dir=3D"auto" class=3D"body markup"><ul><li><p><span>How d=
o you use limited means to achieve aspirational ends? That=E2=80=99s the co=
re idea of </span><em><a href=3D"https://www.robkhenderson.com/p/killing-a-=
bad-strategy-before-it" rel=3D"">On Grand Strategy</a></em><span>, a book I=
 discuss during this livestream.</span></p></li><li><p>Why did Mao Zedong s=
ay "I like to deal with rightists. They say what they really think=E2=80=94=
not like the leftists, who say one thing and mean another." I suggest that =
Mao was able to say this out loud for the same reason that only Nixon could=
 go to China. </p></li><li><p>The hidden trap of having a =E2=80=9Cbig idea=
.=E2=80=9D How even good concepts (including my own =E2=80=9Cluxury beliefs=
=E2=80=9D idea) can become intellectual crutches if you overuse them. </p><=
/li><li><p>Foxes vs. Hedgehogs. Isaiah Berlin=E2=80=99s classic essay, Phil=
 Tetlock=E2=80=99s research, and why the best forecasters embrace complexit=
y over rigid ideology. The media loves bold, simplistic thinkers. But histo=
ry favors those who adapt.</p></li><li><p>Holding two opposing ideas in min=
d while retaining the ability to function.</p><div class=3D"paywall-jump" d=
ata-component-name=3D"PaywallToDOM"></div></li><li><p>Why =E2=80=9Cplans ar=
e useless, but planning is essential.=E2=80=9D A lesson from war strategy t=
hat applies to everything=E2=80=94business, politics, and your personal lif=
e. How preparation=E2=80=94not instinct=E2=80=94separates winners from lose=
rs when chaos hits.</p></li><li><p>Personal responsibility vs. systemic cha=
llenges. Can you acknowledge the unfairness of life while still insisting o=
n personal agency? I argue you have to.</p></li><li><p>Great strategies eme=
rge before they are articulated. How history=E2=80=99s best leaders, from C=
aesar Augustus to Sun Tzu, figured out what worked before writing it down.<=
/p></li><li><p>Machiavelli=E2=80=99s brutal truth. Some moral principles ca=
nnot be reconciled. Justice and mercy, fairness and freedom=E2=80=94why gov=
erning always means choosing. When ideals require breaking other ideals. Th=
e uncomfortable truth about power, morality, and why grand strategy often f=
orces us to choose between competing values.</p></li><li><p>Rationality is =
a tool, not a purpose. If you make logic your ultimate goal, you may win ev=
ery argument=E2=80=94but lose at life. Overthinking can be a liability when=
 decisive action is needed.</p></li><li><p>You don=E2=80=99t need to justif=
y every belief. Love, loyalty, and purpose don=E2=80=99t need a rational ex=
planation to be real. If you question every decision with cold, rational co=
st-benefit analysis, you=E2=80=99ll optimize your way into loneliness. Why =
trying to fit every part of your life into a perfectly rational framework i=
s a losing battle.</p></li><li><p>Books as mental scaffolding. Your own lif=
e won=E2=80=99t provide enough lessons=E2=80=94so you need to learn from ot=
hers=E2=80=99 experiences, mistakes, and victories.</p></li></ul><p>Join me=
 for my next live video in the app.</p><div class=3D"install-substack-app-e=
