span>The Mike Tyson quote is just a modern gloss on the oft repeated =E2=80=
=9CNo plan survives first contact with the enemy=E2=80=9D from German milit=
ary strategist Helmuth von Moltke.</span></p><p><span>The point about train=
ing is a good one. The purpose of traing is to build habits, and that is wh=
at controls a host if human behavior, especially when it is hard to think c=
learly. This is true not just in the military, but in romantic relationship=
s too. As a Loveline listener you'll see this in callers reprising the envi=
ronment in which they grew up in their adult relationships.</span></p><p><s=
pan>Why is this? I think the answer is related to the structure of the huma=
n brain which is relative slow at processing but *massively* parallel. Char=
acteristics that the fact that make it very good at identifying patterns. (=
An insight I credit to Ray Kurzweil.) This brings to mind a recent comment =
of Marc Andreesen that LLMs just predicting  what text follows prior text, =
is more like how humans think than we care to acknowledge.</span></p><p><sp=
an>In any event, I curious if you have thoughts on this as someone who stud=
ies psychology, so I leave this comment!</span></p><div role=3D"button" cla=
